gomodel:SYNGO_1114  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Automated change 2024-03-14: GO:0099056 replaced by GO:0042734" , "Rationale: Immuno EM in afferent terminals of rat DRG.\n\n8/9/2017 Pim\n- Based on the known transmembrane topology of the protein, the \"integral component of ... membrane\" term was chosen.\n- Afferent input into DRG is known to be glutamatergic. Experimental description: All animals were treated according to the guidelines of the Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee (IACUC) of the University of North Carolina. Sprague-Dawley rats (200-300 g, Charles River, Raleigh, NC) were deeply anesthetized with sodium pentobarbital (60 mg/kg, i.p.) and perfused through the heart with 100 ml normal saline, containing 500U heparin sodium at room temperature, followed by either 1 or 4% paraformaldehyde (PF) in phosphate buffer (PB, 0.1 M, pH 7.4). Lumbar segments of spinal cord and L4 DRG were removed and post-fixed for 2 h at 4 8C in the fixative used for perfusion. Blocks of spinal cord were embedded in agar, cut transversely at 70 mm on a Vibratome and stored in PB at 4 8C for up to 2 days before processing. The L4 DRG were cryoprotected in 30% sucrose in PB overnight at 4 8C, embedded in Tissue-Tek O.C.T. compound (Sakura Finetek, Torrance, CA), and sectioned on a cryostat at 15 mm. Every 6th section was thaw-mounted onto pre-cleaned slides and stored at K20 8C." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9425-2935" ;
        dc:date           "2024-03-14" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_1114" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

